JEWISH MOTHERS ALWAYS WANTED THEIR SONS TO BE DOCTORS... Dr. Ephraim Bueno (Bonus), as portrayed by Rembrandt in 1647. Born in Portugal and died in Amsterdam, Ephraim belonged to one of the most important Jewish medical dynasties of the 17th Century. The portrait can be seen at the Metropolitan museum of Art in New York

Amsterdam week 1.: Bronze relief in the cobblestone of Oudekerksplein
Oudekerksplein, Amsterdam, Holland Embedded into the sidewalk, between the sidewalk stones of the Oudekerksplein and the square that surrounds the Old Church in the Red Light District is a bronze/iron sculpture of a hand caressing a breast. The artist is unknown. This sculpture was left secretly in the wee hours of the night. Over the last 15 years, this same unknown artist has placed numerous bronze and iron statues all over town, anomynously in the night. It's been discovered the artist is a local doctor who does the art in his spare time. The City of Amsterdam has since accepted his works as long as the identity of the artist is never revealed. This particular sculpture is a bronze female bust on the pavement in front of the Oude Kerk on Oudekerksplein square. It represents the women of the Red Light District.
Source: http://www.panoramio.com/photo_explorer#view=photo&position=10858&with_photo_id=31725223&order=date_desc&user=4101403 and http://members.virtualtourist.com/m/20ad6/71211/6/
